Linne2013SprayImaging	Article	true	Linne, M.	2013	Imaging in the optically dense regions of a spray: A review of developing techniques	Progress in Energy and Combustion Science		39	5	403-440	10.1016/j.pecs.2013.06.001					https://doi.org/10.1016/j.pecs.2013.06.001	manual_required		No clearly legal open PDF/HTML download was found automatically; use the DOI/URL manually or through institutional access if needed.	thesis.tex:112 || thesis.tex:261 || thesis.tex:264 || thesis.tex:271 || thesis.tex:295 || thesis.tex:321 || thesis.tex:901 || thesis.tex:1084	thesis_zh.tex:117 || thesis_zh.tex:243 || thesis_zh.tex:246 || thesis_zh.tex:258 || thesis_zh.tex:265 || thesis_zh.tex:696 || thesis_zh.tex:698 || thesis_zh.tex:879	Optical spray experiments occupy a complementary niche: under controlled conditions, they provide repeatable and directly comparable evidence of the liquid envelope, and high-speed Mie imaging is especially suitable for observing liquid-phase boundaries and macroscopic penetration evolution \cite{Linne2013SprayImaging}. || Mie scattering is the workhorse for visualising dense liquid sprays for combining the strengths of high temporal resolution with a comparatively simple experimental setup \cite{Linne2013SprayImaging}. || Scattering response depends on droplet size, refractive index, wavelength, and viewing geometry; dense regions add multiple scattering and shadowing on top \cite{BohrenHuffman2004,Linne2013SprayImaging}. || Operational observables --- penetration, cone angle, projected area, boundary location --- are defensible in a way that claims about exact liquid distribution are not \cite{Linne2013SprayImaging,LefebvreMcDonell2017}. || Mie scattering, by contrast, is sensitive to forward and side scattering from liquid droplets and gives high contrast at the liquid-phase boundary under exactly these non-reactive, non-evaporative conditions \cite{Linne2013SprayImaging}, making it the best-matched modality for the penetration and cone-angle observables the thesis extracts. || Mie imaging also brings a characteristic multiple-scattering limitation: in the dense liquid-core region near the nozzle, repeated scattering and internal shadowing elevate the local intensity but contribute almost no sharp directional structure, producing a diffuse halo instead of a clean plume boundary \cite{BohrenHuffman2004,Linne2013SprayImaging}. || This sequence is important for Mie videos because the raw intensity is not a direct measure of liquid volume fraction, and because the practical objective is stable geometry extraction under non-uniform illumination, glare, and background texture rather than exact optical inversion \cite{BohrenHuffman2004,Linne2013SprayImaging,GonzalezWoodsDIP}. || These metrics matter because they turn each aligned strip into a compact geometric state vector; however, the downstream modeling in this thesis remains focused on penetration, which is the best-supported target in the available analyses \cite{Linne2013SprayImaging,LefebvreMcDonell2017}.	šłéś≠§ŚźĆśó∂ÔľĆŚÖČŚ≠¶ŚĖ∑ťõĺŚģěť™ĆŤÉĹŚ§üŚú®ŚŹóśéßÁéĮŚĘÉšłčśŹźšĺõŚŹĮťáćŚ§ć„ÄĀŚŹĮś®™ŚźĎśĮĒŤĺÉÁöĄś∂≤ÁõłŚĆÖÁĽúŤĮĀśćģÔľĆ ťęėťÄü Mie śąźŚÉŹŚį§ŚÖ∂ťÄāŚźąŤßāŚĮüś∂≤ÁõłŤĺĻÁēĆŚíĆŚģŹŤßāÁ©Ņś∑ĪśľĒŚĆĖ \cite{Linne2013SprayImaging}„Äā || Mie śē£ŚįĄŤĘęŚĻŅś≥õÁĒ®šļéŤáīŚĮÜś∂≤ÁõłŚĖ∑ťõĺŚŹĮŤßÜŚĆĖÔľĆšłÄšł™ťáćŤ¶ĀŚéüŚõ†Śú®šļéŚÖ∂Śģěť™ĆŚģěÁéįÁõłŚĮĻÁģÄśīĀÔľõ šłéŤģłŚ§öśõŅšĽ£ŤĮäśĖ≠śČčśģĶÁõłśĮĒÔľĆMie śąźŚÉŹśõīśėďšłéťęėťÄüśĎĄŚĹĪŚĻ≥ŚŹįÁĽďŚźąÔľĆšĽéŤÄĆŤé∑ŚĺóŤĺÉťęėśó∂ťóīŚąÜŤĺ®Áéá \cite{Linne2013SprayImaging}„Äā || ŚÖ∂śē£ŚįĄŚďćŚļĒŚŹĖŚÜ≥šļéś∂≤śĽīŚįļŚĮł„ÄĀśäėŚįĄÁéá„ÄĀś≥ĘťēŅŚíĆŤßāśĶčŚá†šĹēÔľõŚú®ŤáīŚĮÜŚĆļŚüüšł≠ÔľĆŚ§öťáćśē£ŚįĄŚíĆťėīŚĹĪśēąŚļĒŤŅėšľöŤŅõšłÄś≠•śĒĻŚŹėŚõĺŚÉŹŚľļŚļ¶ŚąÜŚłÉ \cite{BohrenHuffman2004,Linne2013SprayImaging}„Äā || ŤŅôšļõśĖĻś≥ēŚĚáŚÖ∑śúČŚźĄŤá™šĽ∑ŚÄľÔľĆšĹÜŚĮĻšļéśú¨śĖáŚÖ≥ś≥®ÁöĄťĚěŤíłŚŹĎ„ÄĀťĚěŚŹćŚļĒś∂≤Áõłśüīś≤ĻŚĖ∑ťõĺŤÄĆŤ®ÄÔľĆŚģÉšĽ¨šłéÁõģś†áŤßāśĶčťáŹÁöĄŚĆĻťÖćÁ®čŚļ¶ŚĻ∂šłćÁõłŚźĆÔľö LIF„ÄĀPIV ŚíĆ PDPA śõīŚĀŹŚźĎÁĽĄŚąÜ„ÄĀśĶĀŚúļśąĖŚćēÁāĻÁ≤íŚĺĄťÄüŚļ¶śĶčťáŹÔľĆťöĺšĽ•Áõīśé•śĒĮśíĎśú¨śĖáśČÄťúÄÁöĄťęėśó∂ťóīŚąÜŤĺ