KendallGal2017	InProceedings	true	Kendall, Alex and Gal, Yarin	2017	What Uncertainties Do We Need in Bayesian Deep Learning for Computer Vision?	Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems 30				5574-5584		https://papers.nips.cc/paper/7141-what-uncertainties-do-we-need				https://papers.nips.cc/paper/7141-what-uncertainties-do-we-need	downloaded	reference_sources/KendallGal2017.pdf		thesis.tex:184 || thesis.tex:612 || thesis.tex:618 || thesis.tex:644	thesis_zh.tex:180 || thesis_zh.tex:436 || thesis_zh.tex:441 || thesis_zh.tex:460	Stage~1 establishes a stable mean-trajectory baseline from representative curves; Stage~2 widens the supervision to the full filtered dataset and learns heteroscedastic conditional variance, because plume-to-plume and shot-to-shot spread are engineering-relevant rather than disposable noise \cite{KendallGal2017}; and Stage~3 reintroduces raw CDF penetration as supervision in the early-time regime where observations remain reliable, while falling back on teacher guidance where late-time observations become sparse. || , providing an error bar width that varies with conditions for each operating point; see Section~\ref{sec:methods-terminology}) \cite{KendallGal2017}. || In regression terms, this corresponds to the conditional model \[ y=\mu(x,t)+\varepsilon(x,t),\qquad \varepsilon(x,t)\sim \mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2(x,t)), \] which should be read here as a pragmatic statistical assumption rather than as a claim that the spray physics are literally Gaussian at every instant \cite{BishopPRML2006,KendallGal2017}. || In this application the two directions produce near-identical predictions in the operating range that matters, and forward KL was retained mainly because it is consistent with the negative log-likelihood objective already used in Stages 1 and 2 \cite{BishopPRML2006,KendallGal2017}.	Stage~1 ÁĒ®šĽ£Ť°®śÄßśõ≤ÁļŅŚĽļÁęčÁ®≥ŚģöŚĚáŚÄľŚüļÁļŅÔľõ Stage~2 ŚįÜÁõĎÁĚ£śČ©ŚĪēŤá≥ŚģĆśēīŤŅáśĽ§śēįśćģťõÜŚĻ∂Ś≠¶šĻ†ŚľāśĖĻŚ∑ģśĚ°šĽ∂śĖĻŚ∑ģÔľĆ Śõ†šłļŚĖ∑ś≤ĻśĚüťóī